    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Small, dainty annual which branches from the base. The upright stems bear backward-pointing hairs and blunt, hairy, lance-shaped leaves. The attractive flowers are borne on branching spikes that extend up above the leaves. Each flower has five flat, white-to-mauve, heart-shaped petals arranged around a central yellow star that leads into a deep throat fringed by hairs and containing two stamens.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_9897",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Stems 60-300 mm long; flowers up to 10 mm across.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_9898",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Coastal regions in the S.W. Cape from about Saldanha Bay to Pearly Beach. Also inland in Namaqualand and Karoo.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_9899",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>The long-tubed flowers in this genus are mostly strongly-scented and pollinated at night by hawk-moths, but in this species the flowers are open during the day, are not scented and are pollinated by long-proboscis bee-flies. The yellow star in the centre changes to pink after pollination and this is though to be a signal to the flies that nectar is no longer available!</p><p>Can be grown from seed and used as an ornamental in coastal gardens.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_9900",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_9901",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers July to November.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_9902",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are over 50 species in this genus in South Africa, of which at least 17 species occur in the fynbos region. The mini-drumsticks <i>Z. parviflora</i> has minute flowers that are cream with a yellow centre. The Sandvelt drumsticks <i>Z. affinis</i> has scented white flowers that close during the day and open at might to attract pollinating moths.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_9903",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
